    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1943-02-09T06:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1943-02-09T06:00:00-05:00" n="243"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d243">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">760C.61/995: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in the Soviet Union</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Standley</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Kuibyshev</hi> (<hi rend="smallcaps"
                            >Moscow</hi>)</placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian"
                            when="1943-02-09T14:00:00+03:00">February 9, 1943—2 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/> [Received February 10—12:15 a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>138. The Polish Chargé d’Affaires<note n="34" xml:id="d243fn34">Henryk
                        Sokolnicki.</note> informed me yesterday that there has been no change or
                    improvement in Polish-Soviet relations.<note n="35" xml:id="d243fn35">See
                        telegram Polish Series No. 3, January 28, midnight, from the Ambassador to
                        the Polish Government in Exile, and footnote 20, <ref target="#pg_323">p.
                            323</ref>.</note> He stated somewhat resignedly that the Soviet
                    Government was still adamant in respect to the release of Polish officers, the
                    evacuation of <pb facs="0343" n="331" xml:id="pg_331"/> Polish women and
                    children and its policy toward Polish Jews. He said that Polish citizens are now
                    being conscripted into the Red Army in spite of the protests of the Polish
                    Embassy.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Standley</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
